external_knowledge:
- "nurturing teachers" refers to teachers with the highest average student scores;
- "at least five students under their guidance" means the teacher has assessed at least 5 students;
- "garden of education" is a metaphorical expression referring to the educational environment or system.

- "blossomed into gardens of learning" refers to schools that have shown significant academic improvement and high average scores;
- "average district score" is the mean score of all students in the district;
- "average district improvement rate" is the mean improvement rate of all students in the district;
- "average school score" is the mean score of all students in the school;
- "average school improvement rate" is the mean improvement rate of all students in the school;
- "thriving educational environments" refers to schools and districts that meet the specified performance criteria.

- "shining star in the realm of Math" refers to the student with the highest score in Math assessments;
- "educational fortress" refers to the school;
- "wise guide" refers to the teacher.

- 'West' refers to a geographic region in the United States that includes states like California, Oregon, and Washington;
- 'assessments of medium difficulty' are standardized tests designed to evaluate student performance at an intermediate level of challenge;
- The 'average Math score' is the mean score achieved by students in the Math section of these assessments.

- "shines the brightest" refers to the district with the highest number of students from top-ranked schools;
- "stand at the pinnacle" refers to schools with the highest average composite scores within their districts;
- "largest number of students" refers to the highest count of students from the top-ranked schools.

- "beacon of prosperity" refers to the state with the highest average median income;
- "average median income" is the mean of the median incomes across all districts in the state;
- "graduation rate" is the mean of the graduation rates across all districts in the state.

- "Western region" refers to a specific geographic area in the country;
- "average performance score" is calculated by averaging the `avg_score` values for each state;
- "soaring above the horizon of 15" means the average performance score is greater than 15.

- "blossoming minds" refers to students who are between the ages of 13 and 18;
- "don’t rely on the free lunch program" means students who do not qualify for free or reduced-price lunch;
- "academic achievements surpass the general growth of their peers" means students whose average scores are higher than the overall average score of all students.

- "Top-performing districts" are determined by the highest average scores across all assessments;
- "Total schools" refers to the number of schools within the district that are included in the top-performing schools;
- "Total assessments" refers to the number of different assessments taken by students within the district;
- "Total students" refers to the number of students who took the assessments in the district.

- "performance trend ID is not null" indicates that there is a recorded trend in student performance;
- "improvement rate > 0" means that the performance has shown a positive improvement over the previous year;
- "average number of students > 1000" implies that the region has a substantial student population;
- "ordered by average median income" suggests that the region with the highest average median income is prioritized;
- "LIMIT 1" ensures that only the top region is selected.

- "average performance scores" refer to the average of the average composite scores for each district;
- "more than 500 students" indicates that only districts with a total number of students exceeding 500 are considered;
- "highest average performance scores" means the districts with the greatest average composite scores are ranked at the top.

- 'Classroom size' refers to the number of students per teacher in a classroom;
- 'Median income' and 'education spending' are economic indicators for the state;
- 'Enrollment' is the total number of students enrolled in a school.
